## 🏗️ Architecture

             ┌──────────────┐
yfinance ───► │ ingestion.py │ fetch_many() └──────┬───────┘ │ ┌──────▼───────┐ │ cleaner.py │ clean_data() └──────┬───────┘ │ ┌──────▼───────┐ │ database.py │ save_data() → SQLite (prices) └──────┬───────┘ │ load_data() / query() ┌─────────────┼─────────────┐ ┌──────▼──────┐ ┌────▼─────┐ ┌──────▼──────┐ │volatility.py│ │ risk.py │ │ analysis.py │ └──────┬──────┘ └────┬─────┘ └─────────────┘ │ │ ┌─▼─────────────▼─┐ │ dashboard.py │ Streamlit UI └──────────────────┘


---

## 📐 The Math Behind It

**Value-at-Risk (Historical Method)**
For a confidence level *c*, VaR is the `(1-c)` percentile of daily returns:
> *"At 95% confidence, losses will exceed the VaR threshold on only 5% of days."*

**Conditional VaR (Expected Shortfall)**
The mean of all returns *worse than* the VaR threshold — answers *"when things go bad, how bad on average?"*

**Annualized Volatility**
Rolling standard deviation of daily log returns, scaled by √252 (trading days/year).

---

## 🚀 Getting Started

### Prerequisites
- Python 3.10+

### Installation
```bash
git clone https://github.com/<your-username>/MarketWatch.git
cd MarketWatch
python -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate      # Windows: .venv\Scripts\activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
Run the Dashboard
streamlit run dashboard.py
Run the Pipeline (CLI)
python main.py
Run Ad-hoc SQL Analysis
python analysis.py
🧪 Testing
The financial calculations are validated with deterministic unit tests:

pytest -v
Test coverage includes:

VaR is always negative (represents a loss)
CVaR ≤ VaR (the tail average is worse than the threshold)
Higher confidence → larger predicted loss
Volatility is non-negative and computed independently per ticker
Dollar VaR scales linearly with position size
📂 Project Structure
MarketWatch/
├── dashboard.py      # Streamlit interactive dashboard
├── main.py           # CLI pipeline (fetch → store → analyze → plot)
├── ingestion.py      # Yahoo Finance data fetching
├── cleaner.py        # Data cleaning
├── database.py       # SQLite persistence + query layer
├── volatility.py     # Rolling annualized volatility
├── risk.py           # VaR & CVaR calculations
├── analysis.py       # Example SQL analytics queries
├── plotter.py        # Matplotlib charting utilities
├── tests/            # pytest unit tests
│   ├── test_risk.py
│   └── test_volatility.py
└── requirements.txt
